==English==

===Etymology===
From {{L.}} {{term|lang=la|id est||that is}}.

===Pronunciation===
* {{a|RP|US}} {{IPA|/ˌaɪˈi:/}}
* {{audio|en-us-i.e..ogg|Audio (US)}}

==={{abbreviation}}===
'''i.e.'''

# {{context|[[initialism]]}} That is; in other words; that is to say; in [[essence]].
#: ''The three U.S. states on the west coast ('''i.e.''' Washington, Oregon, and California) have favorable climates.''

====Usage notes====
*Use '''i.e.''' to explain or clarify a statement by either (exhaustively) listing options or by rephrasing the previous statement.
*American English demands a comma after '''i.e.'''; in British English comma does not follow '''i.e.''' [http://dictionary.reference.com/help/faq/language/g58.html]
*Opinion is mixed about whether the abbreviation should be italicized, or whether there should be a separating non-breaking space as in '''i.&nbsp;e.'''.
*'''ie:''' is often found in current usage, and is perhaps now considered acceptable.

